# 🔍 Detection Rule: Password Spraying Attack

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 1. Objective

Detect password spraying attacks where a single password is attempted
across multiple user accounts to avoid lockouts.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 2. Log Sources

-   Windows Security Logs (Event ID 4625)
-   Azure AD Sign-in Logs
-   VPN Authentication Logs
-   SIEM Authentication Logs

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 3. Detection Logic

Trigger alert when:

-   Same source IP attempts login to multiple users
-   Failed login attempts distributed across many accounts
-   Low frequency attempts to avoid lockouts

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 4. Detection Queries

### Splunk

    index=auth_logs EventCode=4625
    | stats count by src_ip, user
    | where count > 5

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### KQL

    SigninLogs
    | where ResultType != 0
    | summarize count() by IPAddress, UserPrincipalName
    | where count_ > 5

------------------------------------------------------------------------

### Multi-User Detection (KQL)

    SigninLogs
    | summarize UsersTargeted = dcount(UserPrincipalName) by IPAddress
    | where UsersTargeted > 5

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 5. Tuning & Thresholds

-   Adjust user count threshold (5--20 users)
-   Exclude internal IP ranges
-   Filter out service accounts
-   Tune based on login patterns

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 6. False Positives

-   Users sharing VPN IPs
-   Misconfigured applications
-   Password sync issues

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 7. Severity

-   Low: Few users targeted
-   Medium: Multiple users, no success
-   High: Successful login observed
-   Critical: Multiple accounts compromised

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 8. MITRE ATT&CK Mapping

-   T1110.003 --- Password Spraying

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 9. Analyst Notes

Key difference from brute force:

-   Brute force → many passwords, one user
-   Password spraying → one password, many users

Attackers use this method to bypass account lockout protections.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 10. Recommended Response

-   Block source IP
-   Enforce MFA
-   Monitor affected accounts
-   Reset passwords if compromise suspected

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 11. Improvements

-   Combine with geo-location detection
-   Correlate with successful logins
-   Add anomaly detection models
